<h2>1. Let it out</h2>
<p>One of the best things we can do when we’re not feeling good is let it out. If you can, write down what’s upsetting you. Studies have found that writing down what’s on your mind can be better than talking it out, as it helps you make sense and process what you’re feeling.
</p>
<p>So grab some paper and a pen, or draft it on your phone, and try writing from one of these prompts:
</p>
 
<ul>
    <li>How’s your day going?</li>
    <li>If your life was a story how would it go?</li>
</ul>

<p>It doesn’t matter how your spelling is, or what your punctuation is like. It’s about getting those feelings out, working out what’s bothering you, why, and how you can rephrase it into a better light.
</p>

<p>If writing isn’t your thing then turn what you’re feeling into something else. Draw a picture, create music, or a song, take photos of things that express how you’re feeling. These activities have all been shown to help process our feelings.</p>

<p>Lastly, but most importantly, let it out by crying. If you hold any shame about it, don’t, as there’s a good reason we’ve developed crying, it makes us feel better. So have a good sob. If it helps, you could watch a sad film or listen to sad music.
</p>

<p>It’s not only ok to cry, it is genuinely good for you.
</p>

